d the media's influence in shaping American thinking.Taking South Park Seriously brings together scholars who explore the broader implications of South Park's immense popularity by examining the program's politics, aesthetics, and cultural impact. Topics covered include the pleasures of watching the show, South Park's relationship to other animated programs, and the program's representations of racial and ethnic minorities, the disabled, celebrities, children, religion, and education. This book will be of interest not only to communications and cultural studies scholars, but to anyone who has ever laughed along with Cartman, Stan, Kyle, and Kenny.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aAmerican Studies : American Culture. 4aAmerican Studies : American Studies. 4aCommunication : Communication. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Critique. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh1 aBecker, Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyd, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, Lindsay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelashmutt, Michael W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFallows, Randall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroening, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalsall, Alison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHancock, Brannon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOtt, Brian L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlamondon, Marc R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRennie, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab